President Obama has announced his intent to nominate John Koskinen as the Commissioner of the Internal Revenue Service (IRS). Obama stated that Koskinen is experienced in turning around institutions in need of reform and knows how to lead in difficult times. Koskinen has served in various leadership positions in both the private and public sectors, including as Non-Executive Chairman of Freddie Mac, President of the United States Soccer Foundation, Deputy Mayor and City Administrator of Washington, D.C., and Deputy Director for Management of the Office of Management and Budget. He has also worked for the Palmieri Company for 21 years and practiced law with the firm of Gibson, Dunn and Crutcher. Koskinen currently serves on the boards of AES Corp. and American Capital, Ltd. He received a B.A. from Duke University and an L.L.B. and J.D. from Yale University School of Law. President Obama is confident that Koskinen will restore the public's trust in the IRS.